In article &lt;8909192312.AA01958@clouso.crim.ca&gt; philipp@CLOUSO.CRIM.CA (Philip A. Prindeville) writes:
&gt;I thought the not upgrading to DNS was part of the DoD's measures
&gt;to cut expenditures.  I'm glad someone explained this to me...
&gt;
&gt;-Philip


Jon Postel sent this chain to me for comment.

None of the DOD sites are REQUIRED to run the DNS, either servers or
resolvers.  Its only in the last year or so we've made progress in
getting the names changed out from the .ARPA domain.  That part of the
project should complete sometime in the next 8 months depending on how
fast we can move the Navy over.  

I'm not going to make excuses for these sites except to say that money
as usual is a problem and many sites are running one-off systems.
They would have to pay for software development for each system they
run.  *sigh*  A very expensive proposition.  

Eventually, most of the systems will have to DNS resolvers at least,
but this is going to be dependent on the vendors including the
software as a standard part of their releases.

Mike

